  "explanation": "In determining the appropriate sentence, I must weigh the severity of the crime against the mitigating factors presented. Embezzlement is a serious breach of trust, and stealing $25,000 from an employer warrants a punitive response. However, the defendant has no prior criminal record, which indicates this is an isolated lapse in judgment rather than a pattern of criminal behavior. Furthermore, the defendant has already made efforts to partially repay the stolen funds, showing remorse and a willingness to make the victim whole. Regarding the courtroom interruption, the justice system operates on the principles of law, proportionality, and fairness, not on the emotional outbursts of spectators; therefore, the demand for a 10-year sentence is entirely disregarded. Considering the mitigating factors, a lengthy prison term is unwarranted and counterproductive. A short period of actual incarceration, likely to be followed by probation and a strict mandate to complete restitution, is the most appropriate and just response to balance punishment with rehabilitation.",
  "verdict": 6
